d from pantry shelves to museum vitrines and craftworkers from hobbyists to professionals. The roadside shops introduced a business model that, 70 years later, is widely experienced on a very different but equally "super" highway, the Internet, and their story is a chapter in the pre-history of the modern crafts movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHandicraftzNew York (State)zUpstate New York. 0aRoadside marketingzNew York (State)zUpstate New York. 0aVending standszNew York (State)zUpstate New York. 4aCultural Studies : Popular Culture. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Art History. 4aHistory : American History. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 4aSociology : Rural Sociology. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / Middle Atlantic (DC, DE, MD, NJ, NY, PA).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849330540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438493305423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438493305/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles